00:26:24.690 --> 00:26:28.110
that different researchers have
created for different purposes,

00:26:28.110 --> 00:26:29.480
and sort of put them in one place

00:26:29.480 --> 00:26:31.770
so that other researchers
can find them.

00:26:31.770 --> 00:26:35.570
And so they have a description
of the data set, who created it,

00:26:35.570 --> 00:26:40.570
how many tweets are in it, what
date range, that kind of stuff,

00:26:40.570 --> 00:26:44.120
why they created it,
and then a link to go

00:26:44.120 --> 00:26:46.730
to a repository that's
somewhere else on the web, right,

00:26:46.730 --> 00:26:50.140
so this is just a clearinghouse for
the data sets that live elsewhere,

00:26:50.140 --> 00:26:53.190
and they can download it.

00:26:53.190 --> 00:26:56.660 position:56%
And so once you download it, you end
up with something like this, right,

00:26:56.660 --> 00:26:59.960
a file with a bunch
of numbers in it.

00:26:59.960 --> 00:27:04.310
And so the other application I
thought I'd mention really quick,

00:27:04.310 --> 00:27:08.140
is the hydrator application,
which basically,

00:27:08.140 --> 00:27:10.490
it's a desktop application
you download

00:27:10.490 --> 00:27:12.610
and run on your own workstation.

00:27:12.610 --> 00:27:20.830 position:56%
It will read a data set of tweet IDs
and do what they call hydrate them,

00:27:20.830 --> 00:27:25.640
so turn them back into the data
that is useful for research.

00:27:25.640 --> 00:27:32.230
And one of the other things it does
is it will convert the Twitter JSON

00:27:32.230 --> 00:27:35.420
data to CSV that once
