We ask artists to build temporary
monuments and we ask this

00:29:34.870 --> 00:29:41.620 position:56%
to the public as a way to measure
both the expected, or the municipal,

00:29:41.620 --> 00:29:46.510
and also understand the possible,
the dreamed, the speculative,

00:29:46.510 --> 00:29:50.030
the haunts of the city to
have a more complete vision

00:29:50.030 --> 00:29:52.810
of our historical landscape.

00:29:52.810 --> 00:29:56.280
We're working with 20
artists from around the world

00:29:56.280 --> 00:29:58.630
and around Philadelphia
who are going

00:29:58.630 --> 00:30:02.090
to be building these
monuments in public spaces.

00:30:02.090 --> 00:30:07.730
Some will use the kind of
traditional formats, bronze,

00:30:07.730 --> 00:30:12.210
granite, but others are going to
build their monuments with sound,

00:30:12.210 --> 00:30:15.840
light, performance, interactivity.

00:30:15.840 --> 00:30:20.160
Many of these artists take
on issues of social justice,

00:30:20.160 --> 00:30:24.080
especially around race,
gender, sexuality, class,

00:30:24.080 --> 00:30:26.510
national belonging, to make sure

00:30:26.510 --> 00:30:30.710
that our monumental landscape
represents a city founded

00:30:30.710 --> 00:30:34.690 position:56%
on freedom, justice, and toleration.

00:30:34.690 --> 00:30:37.990
Their works will be sited
around the city of Philadelphia

00:30:37.990 --> 00:30:43.470
in our five central squares
that go back to the 1680s,

00:30:43.470 --> 00:30:46.450
and five neighborhood parks.

00:30:46.450 --> 00:30:51.590
At each of these sites, there's
at least one temporary monument

00:30:51.590 --> 00:30:56.320
and a learning lab, where
we use this research form.

00:30:56.320 --> 00:31:01.940
On this form, we ask the
public to name their monuments,

00:31:01.940 --> 00:31:05.600
place it somewhere in the city,
an address, an intersection,

00:31:05.600 --> 00:31:08.380
a neighborhood, though
that often is broken.

00:31:08.380 --> 00:31:10.170
You'll see in a moment.

00:31:10.170 --> 00:31:16.090
We also ask them in a big open
space to describe or sketch.

00:31:16.090 --> 00:31:21.540 position:56%
In addition, if people want to leave
their home zip code, their age,

00:31:21.540 --> 00:31:26.820
their social media handle,
they can add that on as well.

00:31:26.820 --> 00:31:28.940
This is not the first
time that we've done this.

00:31:28.940 --> 00:31:32.540
Back in 2015 in the
courtyard of City Hall,

00:31:32.540 --> 00:31:34.110
we had our Discovery Phase,

00:31:34.110 --> 00:31:36.780
thanks to the Pew Center
for Arts and Heritage.

00:31:36.780 --> 00:31:41.060
Here, our temporary monument
by the late Terry Adkins,

00:31:41.060 --> 00:31:46.690
was an empty classroom to comment
on educational pride that we have

00:31:46.690 --> 00:31:51.040
in the city, and also the fact of
budget cuts and school closures

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:53.750
that marked our current
civic landscape.

00:31:53.750 --> 00:32:00.580 position:56%
In addition to this classroom, we
had the different kind of classroom,

00:32:00.580 --> 00:32:05.750 position:56%
the learning lab, where teams mostly
of youth researchers from college

00:32:05.750 --> 00:32:09.090
and high school would
gather public proposals.

00:32:09.090 --> 00:32:13.350
In the three and a half weeks that
we were in the City Hall courtyard,

00:32:13.350 --> 00:32:23.780
we had 455 people leave monument
proposals, we had 4000 people come

00:32:23.780 --> 00:32:31.190 position:56%
to free programs every day, and over
30,000 people visit the monument.

00:32:32.250 --> 00:32:38.330
When you see these pieces here,
this comprises an imagination

00:32:38.330 --> 00:32:43.560
of the city, and on one hand each
piece matters and the data set

00:32:43.560 --> 00:32:47.520
as a whole both stand out.

00:32:47.520 --> 00:32:53.240
For each piece, it can be seen
in the lab itself at a museum

00:32:53.240 --> 00:32:57.400
or gallery and is deposited
in a local library.

00:32:57.400 --> 00:33:00.040
Some snapshots here.

00:33:00.040 --> 00:33:04.980
Dancing with love in your step,
right in the heart of the city.

00:33:04.980 --> 00:33:10.290
Door to door, an imaginative
portal between neighborhoods.

00:33:10.290 --> 00:33:15.940
In the City of Brotherly Love,
I don't love you, but I -- .

00:33:17.120 --> 00:33:22.900
Of course there's poignant and
important forms of truth-telling.

00:33:22.900 --> 00:33:27.480
Someone who's wary of the murder
crisis in our city called attention

00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:31.350
to the shrines around the
city at sites of violence.

00:33:31.350 --> 00:33:36.420
Others were more poetic, blurring
the boundary between the vision

00:33:36.420 --> 00:33:41.200
of a statue or just an
exchange between Philadelphians.

00:33:41.200 --> 00:33:44.510
And then, of course, the complex.

00:33:44.510 --> 00:33:47.980
Like Claes Oldenburg said,
"Proposing monuments is

00:33:47.980 --> 00:33:51.060
like composing with the city."

00:33:51.060 --> 00:33:55.010
In addition to the individuals,
you can see the data set.

00:33:55.010 --> 00:33:59.530
You can see it on a
map, across the city.

00:33:59.530 --> 00:34:04.220
We've also transcribed and
analyzed and done initial level

00:34:04.220 --> 00:34:08.770
of classification that
is on Open Data Philly,

00:34:08.770 --> 00:34:13.950
the portal for civic data in the
city, so alongside crime statistics

00:34:13.950 --> 00:34:20.530
and traffic incidents, this data
set that is powered by speculation,

00:34:20.530 --> 00:34:24.770
by cultural memory, is available.

00:34:24.770 --> 00:34:28.870
Ultimately our goal is to change
the way that we write the history

00:34:28.870 --> 00:34:32.380
of our city together,
and we take up the call

00:34:32.380 --> 00:34:39.210 position:56%
for cultural heritage organizations
to find new ways to bring in voices,

00:34:39.210 --> 00:34:45.030
people, and data, not just
to be powered by imagination,

00:34:45.030 --> 00:34:49.380
but also to co-author the next
chapters of our city's history.

00:34:49.380 --> 00:34:51.680
Thank you.

00:34:55.160 --> 00:34:57.550
&gt;&gt; Hi. My name is Jared Nielsen.

00:34:57.550 --> 00:35:00.650
I'm an artist and instructor at
George Washington University,

00:35:00.650 --> 00:35:04.940
where I teach full
stack web development.

00:35:04.940 --> 00:35:08.790
I recently discovered the
digital collections available

00:35:08.790 --> 00:35:12.390
to the public on LC's website.

00:35:12.390 --> 00:35:13.930
If you haven't discovered
it yourself,

00:35:13.930 --> 00:35:16.220
I highly recommend browsing this.

00:35:16.220 --> 00:35:17.780
You'll lose hours of your day.

00:35:17.780 --> 00:35:19.660
It's a fantastic collection.

00:35:19.660 --> 00:35:24.040
There's on collection in
particular that caught my eye.

00:35:24.040 --> 00:35:26.460 position:56%
There's this pictorial of St. Louis.

00:35:26.460 --> 00:35:31.160
It's a series of plates that were
published as an atlas in 1875

00:35:31.160 --> 00:35:33.280
by the artist Camille Dry.

00:35:33.280 --> 00:35:39.810
This was created at this time as
an act of boosterism by the city

00:35:39.810 --> 00:35:42.510
when they were making a bid to
become the nation's capital,

00:35:42.510 --> 00:35:45.480
but they thought their
position on the Mississippi,

00:35:45.480 --> 00:35:49.860
being a massive trade economic
route was more suitable

00:35:49.860 --> 00:35:53.630
for our nation's future
than this current swamp.

00:35:55.610 --> 00:36:00.400
These plates are incredibly
detailed and beautiful,

00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:02.110
and one other thing I
thought was really interesting

00:36:02.110 --> 00:36:07.750
when I found these is that
there was no technology used

00:36:07.750 --> 00:36:09.050
in their creation.

00:36:09.050 --> 00:36:11.130
There's no airplane,
there's no hot air balloon.

00:36:11.130 --> 00:36:16.780
This was all Camille Dry and
his team beating the pavement,

00:36:16.780 --> 00:36:23.590
making these records, and
then transposing their 2D data

00:36:23.590 --> 00:36:26.700
into a 3D aerial perspective
representation.

00:36:26.700 --> 00:36:30.330
So here's a little more
of the detail here.

00:36:33.460 --> 00:36:40.650
So the atlas was published with
a key that shows you where,

00:36:40.650 --> 00:36:44.990
which plates where they lined up
with their geographic position

00:36:44.990 --> 00:36:48.480
in relation to St. Louis.

00:36:50.330 --> 00:36:51.790
Because these were all hand-drawn,

00:36:51.790 --> 00:36:54.200
some of the plates have
these interesting features

00:36:54.200 --> 00:37:01.770
where a landmark is breaking the
frame and I wanted to keep this

00:37:01.770 --> 00:37:05.390
when I -- well, first, let me
just say when I discovered this,

00:37:05.390 --> 00:37:07.020
I wanted to do something with this.

00:37:07.020 --> 00:37:10.090 position:56%
If we step back to the key, I wanted

00:37:10.090 --> 00:37:15.040
to see all the plates stitched
together as one large map.

00:37:15.040 --> 00:37:18.040
And this is one of the
issues I encountered, though,

00:37:18.040 --> 00:37:19.910
is when stitching these
together, there are a lot

00:37:19.910 --> 00:37:22.420
of these breaks with the frame.

00:37:22.420 --> 00:37:30.980
So I cleaned up all of these,
but I left these landmark details

00:37:30.980 --> 00:37:36.950
and inserted some space
into the map.

00:37:36.950 --> 00:37:39.680
And I had to convert it to
grayscale because this became

00:37:39.680 --> 00:37:45.060 position:56%
such a massive image file that the
only way for me to pull this off was

00:37:45.060 --> 00:37:48.950
to strip out all the colored
data and go grayscale.

00:37:48.950 --> 00:37:56.200
So this is a small
version of the final image,

00:37:56.200 --> 00:37:58.710
which if anyone here
works with digital images,

00:37:58.710 --> 00:38:03.390 position:56%
you know that an image that's 64,000
by 20,000 pixels is a monster.

00:38:03.390 --> 00:38:08.610
So this was -- the size is roughly
like 900 megabytes, so that's huge.

00:38:08.610 --> 00:38:11.220
It was kind of crippling
my workstation.

00:38:11.220 --> 00:38:15.930
Like my GPU was really
struggling to keep up with this.

00:38:15.930 --> 00:38:19.070
So I have a background in
exhibit design in museums also,

00:38:19.070 --> 00:38:22.450
and in a couple exhibits I worked
on, we used open frameworks

00:38:22.450 --> 00:38:29.280 position:56%
and processing to handle interactive
images, and I tried running this

00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:32.360
through those programs and
it was just killing them.

00:38:32.360 --> 00:38:35.350
And I wasn't sure what to
do, so I asked myself --

00:38:35.350 --> 00:38:38.160
my goal is to keep this
interactive in a way

00:38:38.160 --> 00:38:42.770
where the detail wouldn't be lost,
but we could also still have this

00:38:42.770 --> 00:38:44.470
like pulled-out global scope.

00:38:44.470 --> 00:38:46.930
So I thought, well how
does Google Maps work?

00:38:46.930 --> 00:38:49.410
So I googled it, "how
does Google Maps work?"

00:38:49.410 --> 00:38:53.070
And I found this great
framework Leaflet.

00:38:53.070 --> 00:38:55.280
It's an open search
JavaScript library

00:38:55.280 --> 00:38:59.460
that has really great robust
tutorials and it's very,

00:38:59.460 --> 00:39:02.060
very easy and simple to implement.

00:39:02.060 --> 00:39:06.200 position:56%
And through a little more Google-fu,
I found these fantastic [inaudible]

00:39:06.200 --> 00:39:12.130
on GitHub that helped me piece
together this non-geographic

00:39:12.130 --> 00:39:13.430
story map.

00:39:13.430 --> 00:39:19.220
So Leaflet is intended
specifically for geographic maps,

00:39:19.220 --> 00:39:22.990
for geospatial data abstraction
layers, and I was kind

00:39:22.990 --> 00:39:25.810
of perverting it by using
these non-geographical,

00:39:25.810 --> 00:39:27.400
these raster images.

00:39:27.400 --> 00:39:32.410
So I found this one here,
Raster [inaudible] that was key

00:39:32.410 --> 00:39:35.450
in being able to pull this off.

00:39:35.450 --> 00:39:37.640
This is maybe the least
dynamic slide that I have,

00:39:37.640 --> 00:39:39.380
but maybe the most important.

00:39:39.380 --> 00:39:41.700
This is a directory structure.

00:39:41.700 --> 00:39:43.100
This is my file tree.

00:39:43.100 --> 00:39:47.640
When I -- through Leaflet,
I needed to splice

00:39:47.640 --> 00:39:50.770
that big image up into
smaller tiles.

00:39:50.770 --> 00:39:53.480
So here you can see how
the tiles are nested.

00:39:53.480 --> 00:39:56.780
This is like the levels and
these are all the thumbnails.

00:39:56.780 --> 00:39:59.040
And each of these is 256 pixels.

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:03.900 position:56%
So we've all had this experience
when we're on a slow data connection

00:40:03.900 --> 00:40:07.520
and we're using Google Maps and
we see the little squares pop up

00:40:07.520 --> 00:40:09.670
and then they slowly
come into focus.

00:40:09.670 --> 00:40:11.040
That map tiling in action.

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:12.740
You're seeing map tiling happening.

00:40:12.740 --> 00:40:16.570
This is what map tiling
looks like on a server.

00:40:16.570 --> 00:40:20.960
So I'm going to step through
these zoom slides and I want you

00:40:20.960 --> 00:40:23.060
to pay attention to this
upper left hand corner,

00:40:23.060 --> 00:40:25.380
because this is zero,
zero in our coordinates.

00:40:25.380 --> 00:40:27.850
We're going to zoom
in on zero, zero.

00:40:34.420 --> 00:40:39.220
So my map had eight layers and we
just zoomed through eight layers.

00:40:39.220 --> 00:40:42.960
And my time is up, so I
have to move really quickly.

00:40:42.960 --> 00:40:44.820
JavaScript is awesome.

00:40:44.820 --> 00:40:46.120
This is one of the reasons why.

00:40:46.120 --> 00:40:50.650
You can really simply
implement this map yourself.

00:40:50.650 --> 00:40:52.360
That's all it takes.

00:40:52.360 --> 00:40:56.180
I needed help so I asked
the librarian at the LC

00:40:56.180 --> 00:41:00.010
for some background information
on Camille Dry and this map.

00:41:00.010 --> 00:41:02.360
If you haven't used Ask A Librarian
service, I highly recommend it.

00:41:02.360 --> 00:41:05.990
Within a week I received several
scanned PDFs that were highlighted,

00:41:05.990 --> 00:41:10.120
no less, of the pertinent
information that I needed.

00:41:10.120 --> 00:41:13.310
I plugged it into a
JSON file like this,

00:41:13.310 --> 00:41:16.760
and this is the final end result.

00:41:18.570 --> 00:41:22.800
If you want to see it in action,
you can do so at this URL.

00:41:22.800 --> 00:41:27.420
If you want the [inaudible], build
this yourself locally, go here,

00:41:27.420 --> 00:41:30.570
and I wrote a tutorial on
medium that you can find here.

00:41:30.570 --> 00:41:32.870
Thank you.

00:41:37.540 --> 00:41:38.840
&gt;&gt; My name is Bill Ferster.

00:41:38.840 --> 00:41:45.040 position:56%
I'm with the University of Virginia
at the -- actually it's hard to say.

00:41:45.040 --> 00:41:47.430
It's the Science, Humanities, Arts,

00:41:47.430 --> 00:41:51.640
and Humanities Technology
Initiative.

00:41:51.640 --> 00:41:56.290
It's kind of a little
thing, but -- .

00:41:56.290 --> 00:41:57.760 position:56%
So anyway, what I've come here today

00:41:57.760 --> 00:41:59.570
to show you is a tool
called Visualize.

00:41:59.570 --> 00:42:04.110
And Visualize is a tool
that was designed by us

00:42:04.110 --> 00:42:06.250
for use in two different areas.

00:42:06.250 --> 00:42:09.170
One is for teaching classes,

00:42:09.170 --> 00:42:11.860
interactively in a
project-based setting,

00:42:11.860 --> 00:42:15.600
pretty much like what
you saw the people doing,

00:42:15.600 --> 00:42:18.260
the students earlier in.

00:42:18.260 --> 00:42:22.230 position:56%
And also we use it for making
scholarly arguments using historical

00:42:22.230 --> 00:42:24.560
data, using primary
sources, historical data.

00:42:24.560 --> 00:42:34.970 position:56%
So basically what it is, is we've
connected a timeline, a story panel,

00:42:34.970 --> 00:42:39.610
and a slippy map all
together and put it in so

00:42:39.610 --> 00:42:42.530
that you can actually
make things with it.

00:42:42.530 --> 00:42:46.660
And on top of that map, you can
overlay things on top of it,

00:42:46.660 --> 00:42:48.560
and there are geo reference,
and things like that.

00:42:48.560 --> 00:42:51.270
So you can have dots
or things on top of it.

00:42:51.270 --> 00:42:53.340
You can have interactive graphics.

00:42:53.340 --> 00:42:57.720
You can have KML files, which are
basically vector overlays on top

00:42:57.720 --> 00:43:01.510
of it, or historic maps, and
that becomes quite useful.

00:43:04.440 --> 00:43:07.140 position:56%
So also we've got a variety of other
kinds of tools that you can use

00:43:07.140 --> 00:43:08.440
to make your presentation.

00:43:08.440 --> 00:43:12.240 position:56%
So you can -- this is a drawing tool
built in, so you can draw things

00:43:12.240 --> 00:43:15.600
on it, and then you can do, kind of
pan and zoom maps, and Choropleths,

00:43:15.600 --> 00:43:20.810
which are a way of showing data
relationships on top of maps.

00:43:20.810 --> 00:43:24.330
This tool basically
is all web-based,

00:43:24.330 --> 00:43:26.840
and it's very easy to use.

00:43:26.840 --> 00:43:29.480
And the idea is instead of
things like [inaudible],

00:43:29.480 --> 00:43:32.210
which are very robust tools

00:43:32.210 --> 00:43:34.950
for doing geographic
information system type work,

00:43:34.950 --> 00:43:41.580
these are easily used by
humanity scholars or by students.

00:43:41.580 --> 00:43:44.880
And the key to our -- the way that
we've set it up is we've tried

00:43:44.880 --> 00:43:47.120
to use a very distributed process.

00:43:47.120 --> 00:43:50.470
So I came from UVA.

00:43:50.470 --> 00:43:52.560
We had a place called the
Virginia Center for Digital History

00:43:52.560 --> 00:43:57.400 position:56%
that Ed Ayers had started, and we
used to use all databases back then,

00:43:57.400 --> 00:44:01.470
and these very complex [inaudible]
databases, and what really came

00:44:01.470 --> 00:44:05.210
down is humanities scholars
typically have a big table,

00:44:05.210 --> 00:44:09.630
for the most part, and it's X
number of fields about the thing

00:44:09.630 --> 00:44:11.280
and then a whole bunch of events.

00:44:11.280 --> 00:44:13.600
And so what we did is said,
well, we don't need all

00:44:13.600 --> 00:44:16.860
that complicated database.

00:44:16.860 --> 00:44:18.590
Let's try and use a spreadsheet.

00:44:18.590 --> 00:44:21.390 position:56%
And the advantage of using a
spreadsheet is that Google has built

00:44:21.390 --> 00:44:25.120
in all this incredible sharing
techniques within the spreadsheet.

00:44:25.120 --> 00:44:29.220 position:56%
And so -- and the spreadsheet is
connected live to the visualization.

00:44:29.220 --> 00:44:33.120
They told me actually I
couldn't use the internet,

00:44:33.120 --> 00:44:37.220
so I would've actually shown
it live here, but the idea is

00:44:37.220 --> 00:44:40.540
that you change one thing on
the spreadsheet and it changes

00:44:40.540 --> 00:44:43.130
on the visualization, and
it's also stored there

00:44:43.130 --> 00:44:48.130
so people have more
autonomy with their data.

00:44:48.130 --> 00:44:51.930
And for classroom use,
it works out quite well.

00:44:51.930 --> 00:44:58.410
Anyway, so it was funded by the
NEH, which funded us in a variety

00:44:58.410 --> 00:45:02.690
of different projects for the
Digital Humanities Project.

00:45:02.690 --> 00:45:07.300
It's free to use and
HTML-based and open source.

00:45:07.300 --> 00:45:09.870
And anybody can just look on it.

00:45:09.870 --> 00:45:14.680 position:56%
It's www.viseyes.org, and that
brings up a page which has a variety

00:45:14.680 --> 00:45:17.300
of different tools
that we make at Shanti.

00:45:17.300 --> 00:45:19.310
And if you need to get
a hold of me I'm there.

00:45:19.310 --> 00:45:21.610
So thank you.

